x4freetext: Experimental details
The 150 MeV Geel electron Linac GELINA,
giving neutron bursts of 1ns at a rate of 800 Hz. T
Rotary Uranium Target that is struck by an
electron beam with a mean energy of 105 MeV and an
average current of 70 microA.
.White Neutron Source from 2.6 to 20 MeV
.EN (keV) - neutron energy(center of the energy bin)
.EN-RSL-FW (keV) - uncertainty on neutron energy as
full width of the energy bin
.The resolution was 8 ns time-of-flight which
corresponds to 1.12keV at 1MeV and 35.7keV at 10MeV.
The neutron beam was collimated before the fission
chamber and its diameter was of 6.1cm+/-0.1cm, less
than the diameter of the 235-U deposits and than
the diameter of 208-Pb sample.
.Vacuum evaporated deposits, with a total areal density
of 3.066(6)mg/cm2. The chamber had 5 layers, 3 two-
sided and 2 one-sided. The isotopic composition of
the Uranium deposits was 99.826(8)% 235-U,
.Radiogenic 208-Pb metallic sample with a mass of
217.45 g, diameter of 69.9 mm +/-0.1 mm and thickness
of 5.04 mm. Isotopic content: (88.110+-63)% 208-Pb,
The sample diameter was larger than the beam diameter.
Time-of-flight, with a 198.551m flight path.
The neutron flux was measured
with a multilayer 235-U fission chamber placed at
197.214m flight path.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Nucl. En. Agency Nucl. Data Committee reports, No.311 (1992)

x4freetext: "The 235U Fission
Cross Section", in"Nuclear Data Standards for Nuclear
Measurements", 1991 NEANDC/INDC Nuclear Data Standards
File, Ed. H. Conde, NEANDC-311"U", INDC(SEC)-01, OECD
NEA, Paris (1992)
The used values of the 235U(n,f)cross-section were:
EN      MONIT   MONIT-ERR
MeV     B       PER-CENT
The interpolation of the 235U(n,f)cross-section
data was done linearly.
The two HPGe detectors and the fission
chamber recorded simultaneously. The time resolution
of the time coder was 0.5ns. Conventional electronics
was used for both HPGe detectors and fission chamber
and the Constant Fraction Discriminators of the HPGe
detectors were set up on Slow Rise Time Rejection
function. The efficiencies were measured with a
standard point-like source of 152-Eu of 3.1E+4Bq,
using samples of 56-Co and 24-Na produced by neutron
activation.
.4 large volume HPGe detectors, with closed-ended
coaxial geometry. The relative efficiencies at 1.33
MeV and the distances from the sample position to
the detectors were:
Detector     Angle   Rel.-Efficiency     Distance
The energy resolution was around 2.4 keV at 1.332MeV.
The neutron flux was measured with a multilayer
235-U fission chamber. The fission chamber was used
without any change during the measurement campaign
that included Cr-52, Bi-209, Pb-208, Pb-207 and Pb-206
The shape of the neutron flux did not change
during this campaign.
.The differential gamma production cross-sections at
110 and respectively 150 degrees were derived normali-
sing point by point the HPGe yield to the 235-U
fission chamber yield and to the 235U(n,f) cross
section.
.The following corrections were done:
1) Correction for the distance between positions of
the 208-Pb sample and the position of the fission
chamber;
2) Gamma-ray detection efficiency: extended volume
source and self-attenuation of the gamma rays in
the 208-Pb sample means of MCNP(version 4c2)
simulations. The HPGe efficiencies were corrected
for the coincident gamma rays from the 152-Eu
source. This correction was about 1%.
3) For the angular distribution: Gauss quadrature.
4) For multiple scattering and attenuation of the
neutron beam in the 208-Pb sample. This was done
with MCNP(version 4c2) simulations.
5) No acquisition dead time was observed. To avoid
the possible dead time introduced in the HPGe
detectors acquisition system by the pile-up between
the neutron induced events and the gamma-flash
induced events.
6) For the isotopic composition of the Pb-208 sample
7) The 208Pb(n,2ng) and 208Pb(n,3ng) cross-sections
were corrected for the contribution of the (n,xng)
reactions on 207-Pb and 206-Pb. The (n,xng) cross
sections for 207-Pb and 206-Pb measured during the
same campaign. See  L.C.Mihailescu Ph.D. thesis.

x4freetext: Total uncertainties for the cross sections
were deduced by combining partial uncertainties
from various sources in quadrature. Uncertainty
sources considered were:
HPGe efficiencies uncertainties were
almost the same for the two detectors, ranging
from 2.3% at 0.4MeV up to about 5% at 2.6MeV
gamma ray energy.
Fission chamber efficiency uncertainty
* 235U(n,f)cross-section uncertainties are point
dependent and are given above together with the
235U(n,f) cross-sections values;
Statistical counting uncertainties
for HPGe detectors and fission chamber are point
dependent. The statistical counting uncertainties
of the fission chamber yield range from about 1.4%
at 2MeV up to about 3% at 18MeV.
.The analytical expressions employed are detailed in
the above mentioned NIM paper. Together with the list
of uncertainties on the quantities in these expres-
sions listed above this will allow the evaluator to
construct the covariance matrix. See F. Froehner,
JEFF report 18, OECD-NEA, Paris (2000); and
D.L.Smith, Neutron Physics and Nuclear Data in Science
and Technology, Vol.4, OECD-NEA, Paris (1991)

x4freetext: .The total inelastic cross-section was constructed
based on the known 208-Pb level scheme, see REL-REF,
The contribution of the transitions which decay from
above 4.40MeV excitation energy was neglected. Above
4.40 MeV the present values are only a lower limit
for the total inelastic cross-section. The following
transitions were used to construct the total inelastic
cross-section: 2614.53keV, 4085.4keV, 1614.9keV and
4842.1keV. The appropriate branching ratios were used
including the conversion coefficients if relevant

x4freetext: Pb208 level scheme
Observed gamma-rays from the 208Pb(n,n`g) reaction:
Ex(keV)  Jpi  Eg(keV)    P(%)       Pg(%)      alfa
The superscript `a` denotes the gamma-rays used for
the derivation of the total inelastic cross section.
The gamma-rays marked with `b` could not be distingu-
ished from each other. Here, Ex is level excitation
energy, Jpi - the spin and parity of the level, Eg -
the transition gamma-ray energy, P the transition
probability, Pg - the gamma-ray emission probability,
and alfa - the conversion coefficient.
Obtained via INTERNET, A.Plompen, 2008-08-28.
Corresponds to Fig.10 of main reference
